column1: Will NASA's Artemis 1 mission be launched successfully before 1 January 2023?
column6: ['Technology']
Well done, NASA. Well done!
Launched
#BravoZulu
And its gone, to the Moon and beyond (as they said)
Lift off!
Artemis is scheduled to launch today. Even given the newly observed fuel leak, there remain 6 weeks to correct any newly found issues. It may delay again but I predict it will launch in that window.
Another leak. Chances are sinking for a successful launch in 2022. NASA is getting more careful, which is good. If Artemis 1 launches, it will be a success. NASA is not taking any risks anymore.
Down 20% on another leak. Frankenrocket. Perhaps it will work; if not, then the whole plan might get a 2.0 (or 5.0 ;-)
Count Down... sort of started, less than 24 hrs to go

It's still rocket science and it seems to be more complicated than NASA inicially estimatet. A successfully launch is required and NASA gets more carefull and trying to get rid of almost all risks. This process makes it more unlikely th launch this year.
According to the available data that NASA's Artemis 1 moon mission will be the agency's first big step toward returning astronauts to the lunar surface in November.2022
Up 10% since I've been low earlier. "To infinity and beyond" (tm)
https://apnews.com/article/hurricanes-astronomy-space-launches-science-hurricane-nicole-2fe52d1beb74f884c7ee4b531b4b7d60
Based on the recent news there are still planning to lunch it on time
Storm damage seems minimal, but leaving room to discover something very small, or other setbacks. Generally things take longer than we expect so I’m going to err on the side of under the crowd
Up 20%. Pressure TO (edit) launch and perhaps wear and tear on some important components.
(no change) FWIW https://lite.cnn.com/en/article/h_fd189399fdbb7966fd4e4e453061128a
Stormy weather... shields to maximum
another scheduled delay although third effort ...
Lets see how this hurricane impacts things, lowering a bit
Still comfortable with this forecast, next launch windows are Nov 14 and 19.

Up 10% with NASA "plan" to leave it on the pad during Nicole. OTOH I believe there was a significant correlation with the seal leaks and certain exposure to WX. The problem is not fixed; NASA is trying the best they can to mitigate it.

As @dowser also pointed out, the weather might influence or potentially delay the launch, but I deem it unlikely that the rocket will be brought back from the platform when everything else is in place. I am fairly convinced that there will be an appropriate window before 1 January for the launch and that the rocket will not have to be rolled back due to harsh conditions.
Maintaining current forecast
Down 20% for possible storms heading to Florida. NASA won't leave it exposed if it/they develop. (no link)
Still a bit uncertain due to the successful separation. But target date is 14 Nov.
(no change) The whole valve issue is complicated by certain WX conditions.
Still a bit uncertain due to the successful core stage separation requirement. Otherwise, I'd be higher.

Once the monster has been rolled out it's very hard to expect it not to launch. Even with adverse weather all they have to do is to wait for the appropriate window and go. The last roll back was due to a hurricane event which at this point should be unlikely.
Increasing prob based on - nov 14 looks like current target
Agree to alamo, increasing the probability to 95%.
Rocket has been rolled out to launchpad as planned. Weather looks spotty, some precipitation in coming 10 days however plenty of time for launch to take place.
Weather forecast for Kennedy Space Centre is still pretty shitty: https://weather.com/weather/monthly/l/Kennedy+Space+Center+FL+USFL0339:1:US
it is a big complicated never used piece of equipment and NASA has to get it right. I hope it lifts off on time.
There is a week of pretty crappy weather forecasted in November. Even though 2 week forecasts aren't accurate, I'm going to bring this down a little bit.
https://spacenews.com/nasa-pushes-back-artemis-1-launch-to-november/
This NASA Blog Post mentions three launch windows in November: https://blogs.nasa.gov/artemis/2022/10/12/nasa-sets-date-for-next-launch-attempt-for-artemis-i-moon-mission/
This is about as high as I can justify until after lift-off. Even with perfect indications before the last hours of the countdown, scenarios for “no” will remain:
2x back-up launch dates set in November. This reduces weather risk.

Not much news about Artemis I Launch in the past week. ramping up my probability forecast as I learnt that there are no actual humans who's going on the spaceship. Retaining 10% uncertainty for the weather element.
Two backup launches on November 16 and November 18.
Up 20% to be closer to the consensus.
https://blogs.nasa.gov/artemis/2022/10/12/nasa-sets-date-for-next-launch-attempt-for-artemis-i-moon-mission/
Maintaining current forecast
Great info found by @Ben-Daly, makes me comfortable to push this slightly higher. I agree that the main thing that would stand in the way is weather.
NASA is targeting Nov. 14th for the next try. Another attempt could be made in Dec. if this launch fails for some reasons.
Absent evidence that I see, the consensus is still going up. Up 20% to be closer to the crowd.
maintaining current forecast.
I give this question 100% chance.
They've picked another launch date - Nov 14 (https://www.space.com/nasa-artemis-1-moon-launch-november-14). That's a step in the right direction. The last one was delayed for weather reasons.
I think 75% is defensible for two reasons:
https://www.cnn.com/2022/10/12/world/artemis-nasa-launch-date-scn/index.html
Up 20% to be closer to the consensus.

Just updated my forecast. NASA is targeting Nov. 14th for the next launch attempt of Artemis 1. Still a few risks that could cancel the launch, such as leaks from rolling out and weather, but still an overall positive sign.

Increasing my forecast based on NASA data showing the cumulative probability of launch at the 4th attempt is 94.1% (Source Article: Space Shuttle Launch Probability Analysis: Understanding History So We Can Predict the Future). Since the scheduled launch is not until mid-November, I'll have time to continually reevaluate and adjust.
Optimistic about Nov 14th launch.

There are potentially 2 more launch windows before Jan 1st. - nov and dec. Should be the end of hurricane season. Further, it completed all of its dress rehearsal objectives. Rolling from the VAB to the pad has a lot of risk for damage, hence the moderate confidence.
Probably I'm too pessimistic
The forecast comes down to estimating two parameters:
1. There have already been multiple delays and issues even going back to test fires before the failed launch attempts

We are looking at p(weather problems) + p(technical issues) here as far as I can see. Hurricane season in Florida extends to the end of November and we have already had one delay due to weather. Nevertheless, we are heading into the time of year when the weather will start to calm down, and launches can take place in December also. I am going to say it's just about more likely than not and downgrade it if the November one is delayed also.

Weather should have calmed down by November, so they should be able to get it going, its an important mission so it is times like this that everyone pulls together from all sources. Don't see any problem in it lifting off and doing the Frankie 2DMoon - Might only come back 400 years later when Earth is ruled by Lizards all called Jim
(no change) The hurricane season is now into ~Nov. Recovering from Ian will take cycles that might impact in unexpected ways.
Will a launch have delay: 50% (already has been delayed twice actually)
NASA's new launch date is scheduled between Nov 12-27. Two launches have been cancelled due to technical problems and the 3rd because of Hurrican Ian.
NASA's new launch date is scheduled between Nov 12-27. The first two delays were caused by technical problems (sensor and fuel leak) and the third delay was caused by Hurricane Ian.
If they miss once again I will move this forecast way down.
They may kick the tires and light the fires, but the question requires a (lowish) bar for success.
Initial highly subjective forecast. Sure would be nice to finally see that bucket of Shuttle-era bolts fly.

Planned launch in Nov. If that is scheduled and delayed, I'm not sure there is enough time for a reschedule, but given the window of Nov 12-27, there is lots of room for a slight delay as they plan that.
